Look at the clouds under the exhaust plume at around 0:26 to 0:30. They seem to be growing and shrinking with the rumble of the engine. I think it's caused by the intense sound of the engine condensing the water out of the air. Sound is just pressure waves, with high-pressure peaks and low-pressure troughs. Sound waves change the pressure in the air by up to ±20 Pascals (Pa) at 120 dB (the threshold of pain). This is about as loud as a concert or an ambulance siren (right at the sound source, that is). When the pressure of a gas is reduced, it's temperature also decreases. When the temperature drops below the dew point, water condenses out of the air either as droplets on surfaces or as a cloud suspended in the air.

Rocket launches are around 190-200 dB, which is 10,000,000 times louder than 120 dB. Atmospheric pressure is only 100,000 Pa, so the lowest pressure drop any sound could realistically produce would be 100,00 Pa, at which point the pressure is 0. I'm not really sure what the lowest pressure near a Falcon 9 rocket would be, but I'm pretty sure that it would be low enough to drop the temperature below the dew point if we assume the pressure change to be adiabatic (that is, the temperature changes so rapidly that it doesn't have time to be warmed up by the surrounding air).

The air also heats up at the high-pressure regions, so that my be why the clouds seem to quickly pulsate, as they condense then immediately evaporate.
